# C# embedded statements: omit braces when one statement

When a control-flow construct has **exactly one** embedded statement and C# does **not** require a block, **do not** wrap that statement in `{ }`.

## Applies to

`if`, `else`, `while`, `for`, `foreach`, `lock`, and `using` where the body is a single statement (including another single-line `if`/`else` when you intend that shape).

## Do

```csharp
if (value is null)
    return;

if (!TryParse(input, out int n))
    throw new InvalidOperationException("…");

foreach (var item in items)
    Register(item);
```

Keep **one blank line before** `if` / `foreach` (etc.) when not the first statement in the member, per project blank-line rules.

## Do not

Do not add braces solely for a single statement:

```csharp
// Avoid
if (x)
{
    return;
}
```

Use a **block** when the body is more than one statement, when you need scoped `locals`, or when omitting braces would confuse `else` binding or readability.

## Tooling

Repo **`.editorconfig`** sets `csharp_prefer_braces = false` (IDE0011). Apply **only** this rule (avoid unrelated style fixes such as collection expressions) with:

`dotnet format ArchiForge.sln style --diagnostics IDE0011 --severity info`

For whitespace-only layout, `dotnet format ArchiForge.sln whitespace` and the `scripts/format-solution.*` helpers do not run IDE0011; use the command above when you want brace fixes.

Types, methods, properties, and multi-line bodies still use braces per `csharp_new_line_before_open_brace` and normal C# structure.
